727755f-c.text:
Cueens Boulevard, at the S. W. corner of 62nd Avenue, showiigg the Mrs. Howard House, also known as the Robert Odekirk farmhouse and was at one time used as a parsonage by ministers of the Firat Presbyterian Church of Newtown. The house was owned by the R. and J. Thompsons from 1852 to 1896. Later it was purchased by the Rego Park Construction Company and used as a real estste office. The home dates back to pre-Revolutionary days. Eugene L. Armbruster is authority for the above data. View 4 shows the rear of the house.

727757f-b.text:
Queens Boulevard, at the S. W. corner of 62nd Avenue, showing the Mrs. Howard House, a pre-Revolutionary farmhouse. It was at one time a parsonage and was also known as the Robert Odekirk farmhouse. The R. and J. Thompsons were the owners from 1852 to 1896. The Rego Park Construction Company later established its real estate
office here.
View 2 shows the rear of the house, seen from 57th Avenue. In 1936 the house was occupied by the Tomahawk Regular Democratic
Club.
View 1: P. L. Sperr  June 8, 1927
View 2: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection May, 1900
View 3: P. L. Sperr  June 29, 1936
